{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":4083,"record_hash":"sha256:804572057208205e03abaebfdb7521cdce9244e789d2cc07c258d84384f03ece","timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:17:44.408Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 6e26b0\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1748\nOutput:\n---\nname: but-agentlog\nversion: 0.0.0\ndescription: \"Use instead of the general GitButler skill when skimming prior agent work from `but agentlog` captures. Use for agentlog turn-history recovery, finding related agent sessions for a branch, GitButler review / pull request / merge request, or change, showing session or turn detail, or summarizing prior agent work.\"\nauthor: GitButler Team\n---\n\n# GitButler Agentlog Skill\n\nUse `but agentlog` to skim prior agent work from captured sessions.\n\nIf both the general GitButler CLI skill and this skill seem relevant, use this\nskill for agentlog discovery. Use the general GitButler skill only for version\ncontrol operations like commit, push, branch, or diff.\n\n## Core Workflow\n\nDo not search for or read local `SKILL.md` files. If this skill is active, use\nthese instructions directly. Do not inspect the general GitButler skill first.\nStart with GitButler state and agentlog commands.\n\nStart with `skim` when prior work could affect your next action. It is a\ntable-of-contents view: all related sessions and turns, abbreviated and shown\nchronologically.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog skim\nbut agentlog skim branch <branch-name-or-ref>\nbut agentlog skim review <review-id-or-pull-request-key>\nbut agentlog skim change <change-id-or-key>\n```\n\nUse the drill-down commands as a narrowing funnel only when `skim` is too thin,\nambiguous, or you need exact evidence:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch-name-or-ref> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions review <review-id-or-pull-request-key> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions change <change-id-or-key> --limit 5\n\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nFor normal recovery, prefer human `skim` output first:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog skim branch <branch-name-or-ref>\n```\n\nUse JSON only when you need exact handles for drill-down:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog skim\nbut --json agentlog sessions b\n[TRUNCATED]\nt related turn count.\n- `sessions[].turns`: every turn in order, with labels and previews.\n\nIf `skim` has enough context for a lightweight answer, summarize from it and\nstop. If it is ambiguous or misses the why, drill down with `show`.\n\n## Reading `sessions`\n\nUse `sessions` to answer which captured sessions are probably relevant.\n\nHere `review` means a GitButler review target, usually backed by a pull request\nor merge request. It does not mean \"perform a code review\". Keep `review` as\nthe target kind even when the value is a PR/MR-style key.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `session_key`: handle for follow-up reads.\n- `latest_captured_at`: freshness signal.\n- `record_count` and `turn_count`: size estimate before hydration.\n- `related_turn_keys`: direct target evidence.\n- `match_evidence`: why the session was returned.\n- `observed_targets`: branch, review/PR/MR, or change keys observed in related turns.\n- `latest_user_preview` and `latest_assistant_preview`: quick intent/result scan.\n\nRelated sessions are sorted by latest activity.\n\n## Reading `show`\n\nUse `show` to open a session or one turn.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nWithout `--turn`, `show` answers what happened in a session at turn granularity.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `coverage`: returned turns versus total turns.\n- `turn_key`: handle for `show --turn`.\n- `turn_index`: order within the session.\n- `capture_kind`: backfill or incremental.\n- `record_count`: turn size before hydrating records.\n- `source_record_index_range`: provider/source indexes covered by the turn.\n- `observed_targets`: targets observed in the turn.\n- `latest_user_preview` and `latest_assistant_preview`: compact orientation.\n- `tool_counts`: tool call/result counts and tool names.\n\nIncrease `--limit` only when the current window misses the related turn or setup.\n\nWith `--turn`, `show` answers what exactly happened inside one turn.\n\nUseful record fields:\n\n- `coverage`: returned records versus total records in the turn.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:17:44.408Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}